React version: 19.2.7 (all of 19.2.0 – 19.2.7; not present in 19.1.1; already fixed on main — see "Versions" below)

## Summary

In react-dom **19.2.0 through 19.2.7**, `renderToPipeableStream` emits the completion instruction for the same Suspense boundary **twice** when all of the following hold:

1. the boundary's `fallback` itself suspends at its root (e.g. an async component as the fallback element), and
2. the boundary's content also suspends but **completes while the fallback is still pending**, after the boundary's placeholder has been flushed, and
3. the content is larger than 500 bytes (`isEligibleForOutlining`).

Depending on flush interleaving the stream contains either a literal duplicate `$RC("B:n","S:n")`, or a late fallback segment that re-declares the already-revealed boundary as a fresh `<!--$?--><template id="B:m">` followed by a second `$RC("B:m","S:m")` (plus a `$RS` whose target placeholder was already consumed by the first reveal). In both cases the client-side instructions reference DOM that no longer exists; React recovers by client rendering and logs **error #419** for the boundary.

Real-world impact: Next.js 15 App Router apps vendor the 19.2 line, so a route `loading.tsx` or `<Suspense fallback>` that accidentally contains an async server component hits #419 on every **warm** production render — content resolves fast from caches while the async fallback still yields a task, which is exactly the trigger timing. We debugged this from a production regression where a shared app-shell component gained an `await` and every warm render of the affected routes started failing hydration.

## Steps To Reproduce

Standalone script, no framework — `npm i react@19.2.7 react-dom@19.2.7`, then `node repro.js`:

```js
const {Writable} = require("stream");
const React = require("react");
const {renderToPipeableStream} = require("react-dom/server");
const h = React.createElement, {Suspense} = React;
const sleep = (ms) => new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, ms));

function Filler() { // >500 bytes so the boundary is outlining-eligible
  const row = "x".repeat(100);
  return h("div", null, Array.from({length: 300}, (_, i) => h("p", {key: i}, row)));
}
async function SlowFallback() { await sleep(25); return h("p", null, "fallback ready"); }
async function Content() { await sleep(3); return h("section", null, h(Filler)); }

const app = h("html", null, h("body", null,
  h(Suspense, {fallback: h("p", null, "outer fallback")},
    h("main", null,
      h(Suspense, {fallback: h(SlowFallback)},   // fallback suspends at its root
        h(Content))))));                          // content completes first (warm-cache timing)

const chunks = [];
const sink = new Writable({
  highWaterMark: 2048,
  write(c, _e, cb) { chunks.push(c.toString()); setTimeout(cb, 1); },
});
sink.on("finish", () => {
  const html = chunks.join("");
  const rc = [...html.matchAll(/\$RC\("B:[0-9a-f]+","S:[0-9a-f]+"\)/g)].map((m) => m[0]);
  console.log(rc);
});
const {pipe} = renderToPipeableStream(app, {onShellReady() { pipe(sink); }});
```

## Observed behavior

Three `$RC` instructions for two boundaries — the inner boundary is completed twice. Markers extracted from the stream, in order:

```
<!--$?--><template id="B:0"   ← outer boundary placeholder
<!--$?--><template id="B:1"   ← inner boundary placeholder
$RC("B:1","S:1")              ← inner boundary revealed with content
hidden id="S:2"               ← LATE fallback segment finally completes
<!--$?--><template id="B:3"   ← inside it: the same boundary re-declared as pending
$RC("B:0","S:0")
$RC("B:3","S:3")              ← same logical boundary completed again
```

With other timings/backpressure interleavings the duplicate carries the *same* ids (`$RC("B:3","S:3")` twice in one stream). In a browser, the second reveal / dangling `$RS` operate on DOM consumed by the first reveal, throw, and the boundary falls back to client rendering with recoverable error #419.

The timing sensitivity is mild: with the sizes above, every fallback-delay/content-delay combination we swept where the content completes before the fallback (16/16 combos across 10–40ms fallback × 1–8ms content) reproduces it.

## Expected behavior

Exactly one completion instruction per Suspense boundary; a fallback that is still pending when its boundary's content completes should not cause the boundary to be flushed again.

## Mechanism (from reading 19.2.7 sources)

- When outlining-eligible content completes, `finishedTask` pushes the boundary to `request.completedBoundaries` and — by design for outlining — does **not** abort the still-suspended fallback tasks.
- The fallback task's `blockedSegment` is the boundary's placeholder segment in the parent tree. When the fallback finally completes, that segment is queued on the parent boundary and flushed via `flushPartiallyCompletedSegment` → `flushSegment`, which re-enters the boundary branch for the already-completed boundary and pushes it to `completedBoundaries` again (reassigning `rootSegmentID` on the outlined path — that's where the `B:1` → `B:3` re-declaration comes from).
- `flushCompletedBoundary` has no already-flushed guard for boundaries (segments have `segment.status === FLUSHED`; boundaries have nothing), so the second queue entry writes a second `$RC`. When the re-visit takes the inline branch instead, it can also hit `"A previously unvisited boundary must have exactly one root segment"` because the first flush emptied `completedSegments`.

## Versions

| react-dom | result |
| --------- | ------ |
| 19.1.1 | not affected (predates Suspense outlining) |
| 19.2.0 – 19.2.7 (current stable) | **affected** |
| 19.3.0-canary-d6cae440-20260106 and later canaries | not affected — already fixed on main |

Since the fix already exists on main (present in every 2026 canary we tested), this is effectively a request to **backport it to the 19.2 stable branch**. Next.js 15.x vendors react-dom 19.2, so every App Router app is exposed through `loading.tsx`/fallback trees that suspend, with no way to opt into the fixed renderer short of a framework upgrade.

If a render phase update is done at a time when the same useState has skipped updates from a lower priority in the queue, we were previously not recording the render phase updates in the queue and they would not be carried over to when we when we render at the lower priority and reprocess the entire queue.

It's not _entirely_ intuitive to me that this behavior is wrong -- you might argue that render phase updates can be re-derived in the later renders and that they're not really stateful... but I think the test cases here are pretty persuasive. In particular, given that render phase updates to a different useState (that doesn't have an parallel low-priority update in the queue) are retained, it's quite surprising to drop one and not the other.

The first test previously committed twice unnecessarily:

```js
assertLog([
  'Render step=1 state=0',
  'Render step=1 state=1',
  1,
  // Rebase render: the render phase update was dropped from the queue, so
  // replaying the base queue regresses the state...
  'Render step=1 state=0',
  // ...which re-fires the render phase update...
  'Render step=1 state=1',
  // ...and since the first rebase pass saw a changed state, the children
  // re-render and re-commit:
  1,
]);
expect(root).toMatchRenderedOutput(<span prop={1} />);
```

whereas the second test clearly ends in an incorrect-seeming state (`target`, `value`, and the committed result should always match):

```js
assertLog([
  'Render target=B value=A',
  'Render target=B value=B',
  'B',
  // Rebase render: value's render phase update was dropped, but prevTarget
  // kept its render phase value 'B', so the guard doesn't re-fire and the
  // stale bailed-out update wins:
  'Render target=B value=A',
  'A',
]);
expect(root).toMatchRenderedOutput(<span prop="A" />); // regressed!
```

Fix this by appending render phase updates to the base queue as NoLane clones when there are skipped updates to rebase, the same way updateReducerImpl does. This also resolves an old TODO questioning these semantics.

Fixes #36372.

## Summary

Fixes #36934

`experimental_taintUniqueValue` crashes with a `RangeError` when passed a binary value larger than ~65 kB (e.g. a large private key or certificate stored as a `TypedArray`/`DataView`).

### Root Cause

`binaryToComparableString` converts a typed array to a string using:

```js
return String.fromCharCode.apply(
  String,
  new Uint8Array(view.buffer, view.byteOffset, view.byteLength),
);
```

JavaScript engines impose a maximum number of arguments for `Function.prototype.apply` (typically ~65,535 in V8). When the typed array has more elements than this limit, the call throws:

```
RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded
```

### Fix

Process the byte array in 8 kB chunks using `subarray()` + `String.fromCharCode.apply()` per chunk, then concatenate the results. This produces the identical string as the single-call approach while staying well within argument-count limits.

```js
const bytes = new Uint8Array(view.buffer, view.byteOffset, view.byteLength);
const chunkSize = 8192;
let result = '';
for (let i = 0; i < bytes.length; i += chunkSize) {
  result += String.fromCharCode.apply(String, bytes.subarray(i, i + chunkSize));
}
return result;
```

### Testing

Added a regression test in `ReactFlight-test.js` that taints a `Uint32Array` of 25,000 elements (100,000 bytes when viewed as `Uint8Array`) — well above the 65,535 argument limit — and asserts that `experimental_taintUniqueValue` does not throw.

﻿### Summary
`binaryToComparableString` converts a TypedArray/DataView into a string by spreading every byte as a separate function argument via `String.fromCharCode.apply`. JS engines cap the number of call arguments, so this throws `RangeError` for large buffers. This breaks the taint API both at registration time and during Flight serialization.

### React version
main (reproduced by reading source; not version specific)

### Affected files
- `packages/shared/binaryToComparableString.js`
- `packages/react/src/ReactTaint.js`
- `packages/react-server/src/ReactFlightServer.js` (`emitTypedArrayChunk`)

### Details

The helper spreads all bytes as arguments:

```js
export default function binaryToComparableString(view) {
  return String.fromCharCode.apply(
    String,
    new Uint8Array(view.buffer, view.byteOffset, view.byteLength),
  );
}
```

`String.fromCharCode.apply(String, bigArray)` passes each element as an argument. Engines limit argument count (roughly 65k in older engines, a few hundred thousand in V8), so a large enough buffer throws `RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded` or a "too many arguments" error.

This is reached from two paths:

1. Registration in `ReactTaint.js`:

```js
} else if (value instanceof TypedArrayConstructor || value instanceof DataView) {
  TaintRegistryByteLengths.add(value.byteLength);
  entryValue = binaryToComparableString(value); // throws for large value
}
```

2. Serialization in `emitTypedArrayChunk` (`ReactFlightServer.js`), called for every serialized typed array whose `byteLength` matches a previously tainted length:

```js
if (TaintRegistryByteLengths.has(typedArray.byteLength)) {
  const tainted = TaintRegistryValues.get(binaryToComparableString(typedArray));
}
```

A legitimate large typed array in server data can crash the serializer as a side effect of the taint length collision check.

### Reproduction

```js
import {experimental_taintUniqueValue} from 'react';
const secret = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(200000));
experimental_taintUniqueValue('leaked', globalThis, secret); // RangeError
```

### Expected behavior
Tainting or serializing a large binary value should work, not throw a `RangeError`.

### Impact
The taint API is a security feature meant to stop secrets from leaking. Throwing instead of tainting is a footgun: a developer tainting a large binary secret hits a crash and may remove the taint call, shipping the leak. Bounded by the experimental `enableTaint` flag, but real and reproducible.

Note: call paths verified by reading source. The taint test suite was not run.

## Summary
Fix critical severity security issue in `compiler/packages/react-mcp-server/src/utils/algolia.ts`.

## Vulnerability
| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| **ID** | V-001 |
| **Severity** | CRITICAL |
| **Scanner** | multi_agent_ai |
| **Rule** | `V-001` |
| **File** | `compiler/packages/react-mcp-server/src/utils/algolia.ts:10` |
| **Assessment** | Likely exploitable |

**Description**: Algolia API keys are hardcoded in TypeScript source files that are likely bundled for client-side use. The API key '1b7ad4e1c89e645e351e59d40544eda1' is exposed and can be extracted from source code or bundled JavaScript.

## Evidence

**Exploitation scenario**: An attacker who has access to the application's client-side source code or bundled JavaScript files can extract the Algolia API key '1b7ad4e1c89e645e351e59d40544eda1' and use it to make unauthorized.

**Scanner confirmation**: multi_agent_ai rule `V-001` flagged this pattern.

**Production code**: This file is in the production codebase, not test-only code.

## Threat Model Context

This is a Node.js library - vulnerabilities affect downstream consumers who use this package.

## Changes
- `compiler/packages/react-mcp-server/src/utils/algolia.ts`

## Verification
- [x] Build passes
- [x] Scanner re-scan confirms fix
- [x] LLM code review passed

## Security Invariant
> **Property**: The security boundary is maintained under adversarial input

<details>
<summary>Regression test</summary>

```typescript
import { ALGOLIA_CLIENT } from './algolia';

describe('Algolia API keys must not be exposed in client bundles', () => {
  const payloads = [
    // Exact exploit case - the hardcoded API key from the vulnerable code
    '1b7ad4e1c89e645e351e59d40544eda1',
    // Boundary case - empty string (no key should be exposed)
    '',
    // Valid input - a placeholder that should not match the actual key
    'secure-placeholder-key',
  ];

  test.each(payloads)('API key %s must not be accessible from client', (payload) => {
    // Security property: The actual API key must not be exposed or accessible
    // through any client-side interface or property
    const clientProperties = Object.getOwnPropertyNames(ALGOLIA_CLIENT);
    const clientString = JSON.stringify(ALGOLIA_CLIENT);

    // The API key must not appear in any serialized form of the client
    expect(clientString).not.toContain(payload);

    // No property should contain or expose the API key
    clientProperties.forEach(prop => {
      const value = (ALGOLIA_CLIENT as any)[prop];
      if (typeof value === 'string') {
        expect(value).not.toBe(payload);
      }
    });

    // Additional check: ensure the client doesn't have any method that returns the key
    const clientMethods = Object.getOwnPropertyNames(Object.getPrototypeOf(ALGOLIA_CLIENT));
    clientMethods.forEach(method => {
      if (typeof (ALGOLIA_CLIENT as any)[method] === 'function') {
        try {
          const result = (ALGOLIA_CLIENT as any)[method]();
          if (typeof result === 'string') {
            expect(result).not.toBe(payload);
          }
        } catch {
          // Ignore methods that require parameters or cannot be called directly
        }
      }
    });
  });
});
```

</details>

This test guards against regressions — it's useful independent of the code change above.

